Among other points of objection taken by the French, perhaps, the most noticeable is, that he has not observed the sacred unities‚ so hallowed by the practice of their own extolled tragedians. They hold, of course, after Corneille and Racine, that Sophocles is the most perfect model for tragedy, and Aristone its most infallible censor; and that as Hamlet, Lear, Maebeffl, and other dramas by Shakspere, are not framed upon that model, and consequently not subject to the same laws, they maintain (not having impartiality enough to question the model, or to deny the rules of the Stagirite) that Shakspere was a sort of irregular genius—that he is now and then tasteful and touching, but generally incorrect; and, in short, that he was a mere child of nature, who did not know any better than to write as he has written.''
